{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NHJEgwsnndhpsTffvNwJws","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All requirements are met. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**Root cause:** The `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only contained a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`) with no RabbitMQ targets.\n\n**Fix — two changes to the ConfigMap:**\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** pointing to all 3 pods via the existing headless service DNS (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`), which provides stable per-pod DNS records without needing a CRD or operator.\n\n2. **Added a recording rule** (`rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`) in a second ConfigMap key (`rabbitmq.rules.yml`) that's automatically available at `/etc/prometheus/` via the existing volume mount. The native RabbitMQ Prometheus plugin (port 15692) doesn't emit `rabbitmq_up` itself — Prometheus generates the `up` metric internally per scrape target, and the recording rule surfaces it under the expected name.\n\n**Result:**\n- 3 RabbitMQ targets: all `up`\n- `rabbitmq_up` query: 3 samples, each `= 1`\n- All 3 RabbitMQ pods: `Running`, 0 restarts"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":203,"cache_read_input_tokens":38953,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":203},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a56f6da-b743-461b-98f3-9ec9a662da6a","uuid":"5e5fa2d4-aaab-4e52-9988-5df5c5af276e","request_id":"req_011CcLFnfvjQrUmt2Kza22aW"}
